The default behaviour of triggering map initialization on the default `load` event breaks when the map is inserted to DOM with e.g. jQuery. We have the following behaviour in our application which introduces this breakage.

This snippet is rendered on the server side with Django (as a slightly larger version) and fetched with a jQuery AJAX call:

```
    <div class="update map">
            <p>{{ update.address }}</p>
            {% leaflet_map update.uuid.hex %}
    </div>
```

The resulting map is then added to the DOM structure:

```
    var snippet =$(...)
    $('.updates').append(snippet);
```

The default `load` event is oftentimes not fired at all even though there are additional load events happening in the background and the trigger is fired manually with `$(window).trigger('load')`.

I tried replacing the `loadevent` value with a custom event, and indeed the maps never initialized with the custom events firing:

```
    <div class="update map">
            <p>{{ update.address }}</p>
            {% leaflet_map update.uuid.hex loadevent='leaflet_load' %}
    </div>
```

and elsewhere:

```
    $(window).on('leaflet_load', function () {
        console.log('leaflet_load event triggered')
    }

    $(window).trigger('leaflet_load')

    leaflet_load event triggered  // Console outputs correctly

    // No map initialization happens whatsoever
```

After investigating for quite some time I tried setting the `loadevent` templatetag attribute to an empty string as suggested by the documentation:

```
    <div class="update map">
            <p>{{ update.address }}</p>
            {% leaflet_map update.uuid.hex loadevent='' %}
    </div>
```

And this results in correct map loading every time. Leaflet seems to be happy with this and everything is in order. I tested this with newest versions of Internet Explorer, Edge, Chrome, and Firefox. 

Some suspicions

- Event handling with the default `document.addEventListener` or `jQuery(window).on` is broken (what I suspect)
- Appends from AJAX and subsequent templating do not correctly trigger on `load` or other events on the DOM all the time for whatever reason (seems unlikely as manually triggering the events does nothing either);

The snippet that triggers the Leaflet map loading looks like this from the `leaflet_map` template tag which uses the `leaflet/_leaflet_map.html` template.

```
<script type="text/javascript">
(function () {

    function loadmap() {
        var djoptions = {"center": [61.4619999, 23.7507025], "minzoom": 5, "layers": [["OSM", "//{s}.tile.openstreetmap.org/{z}/{x}/{y}.png", "\u00a9 <a href=\"http://www.openstreetmap.org/copyright\">OpenStreetMap</a> contributors"]], "attributionprefix": null, "zoom": 14, "overlays": [], "maxzoom": 17, "minimap": true, "tilesextent": [], "scale": "metric", "fitextent": true, "resetview": true, "srid": null, "extent": [[-90, -180], [90, 180]]},
            options = {djoptions: djoptions, initfunc: loadmap,
                       globals: false, callback: initializeLeafletMap};
        L.Map.djangoMap('update-map-3b755938-4af6-4079-9805-e3a668928515', options);
    }
    var loadevents = ['load'];  // 'load' is the default event
    if (loadevents.length === 0) loadmap();
    else if (window.addEventListener) for (var i=0; i<loadevents.length; i++) window.addEventListener(loadevents[i], loadmap, false);
    else if (window.jQuery) jQuery(window).on(loadevents.join(' '), loadmap);
    
})();
</script>
```

And the event handler is this part:

```
    var loadevents = ['load'];
    if (loadevents.length === 0) loadmap();
    else if (window.addEventListener) for (var i=0; i<loadevents.length; i++) window.addEventListener(loadevents[i], loadmap, false);
    else if (window.jQuery) jQuery(window).on(loadevents.join(' '), loadmap);
```

`jQuery` is loaded correctly and globally but nothing happens when I trigger a) the regular `load` or b) any custom events.

Am I missing something with the AJAX DOM handling and events or is this a bug?

This is somewhat related to #211 

I found there is an undocumented option called 'listener' which seems to be called during the parsing of the YAML.  I was hoping to be able to do something during the load in which I could reliably maintain the order of the root elements (i.e. those at lineIndent === 0) e.g.

    const order = []
    function listener(op, state) {
        if(op === 'open' && state.lineIndent === 0 && state.kind === 'scalar')
             order.push({ key: state.result, line: state.line })
    }
    yaml.load(text, { listener })

This seems to work, but I wanted to check my understanding was correct and I can always expect that the listener() function is called in order of parsing.

